n the boundary between the rural southeast and the rest of Northumberla</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd, it has become obvious to me that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">despite its situation, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">most people in Morpeth are not familiar with the location of most of the villages in the rural areas  which lie beyond three or four miles north and west of the town, and they certainly have littl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e or no idea about the lives and work of the people who live there, or what services they may or may not have left to them.  If this is the case in Morpeth, on the edge of the rural area, there is little chance that anyone based in the south east of the co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unty, and from that culture, has any real appreciation of the nature and needs of rural communities, even if they have the best intentions, and have been dealing with council business for the whole of their working lives.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">When the Unitary Authority was cre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ated in Northumberland, there was no official poll, and despite all of the unofficial polls appearing to show that about 90% of Northumberland residents objected to a Unitary Authority, those who had the power to do so forced it through anyway against</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">wishes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of most residents</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Now, for certain issues, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the majority of those </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on the North East Leadership Board </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">who are shaping crucial policies in our name are going to be impossibly remote should we wish to contact them or observe what is being done in our n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ame.  At present, if public transport allows, I can get to County Hall to observe a Policy Board or full Council meeting. It is almost certain that it will be too time consuming </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and expensive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for me to go to observe a North</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> East L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eadership Board meeting, e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ven if </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I was allowed to, given that a high proportion of the matters being discussed under the headings of economic development and regeneration and transport are likely to be commercially sensitive.  It is likely to be remote </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">even from my own County Counc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">il</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lor.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  It is unlikely that the representatives of e.g. Sunderland and Newcastle could have any useful insight into the needs of e.g. Berwick</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-upon-Tweed and the north of Northumberland, which would most probably benefit from making better connections with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Scotland rather than areas south of the Tyne anyway.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">I think that there should be two representatives for Northumberland, one for the 50% of the population who live in the southeast and one for the 50% of the population who live in the rural communities. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Maybe there should be the same arrangement for rural County Durham as well, so that there would at least be some rural voice, even if it was still without any power compared to all of the other urban representatives.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At the very least</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, there should be an e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ffective trial period and means of opting out for the rural areas of Northumberland and County Durham if this arrangement is found not to be working for them. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Before thi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s proposal is allowed to proceed any further t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">here should also be a guaranteed level of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> service, investment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nd protection from cutbacks for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> each community, particularly small rural ones, many of which are already left with only the barest remnants of the services which they once had.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although described in strict accuracy as voluntary, th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is appears to be more a coerced response to current government policy which works against the interests of remote regions and communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.  A proposal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">which is designed less in response to Westminster short termism and more as something which has had time </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to be thoroughly and carefully considered and has grown out of the true long term needs of the region would serve us better.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">B)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">There is not enough detail in the current consultation for us to be able to giv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e a properly informed response</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and as usual, n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ext to no</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one who I have spoken to in the last week has any idea that this is happening, although the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y do have strong views about it when asked.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Though the consultation is on the front page of the Northumberland County Council website, it only says consul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tation and does not say what it is about until people actually go into it. Though many would be likely to have strong feelings about it, they are not likely to go into it unless they are already in the know.  It does not appear in the alerts at the top of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the County Council home page, although more parochial consultations have appeared there in recent weeks, so unless people have time to investigate, they might well think that the consultation is about one of these parochial issues.  I know from speaking to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> people that a significant proportion are cancelling papers such as the Morpeth Herald and the Northumberland Gazette because they are looking for any ways to enable  their income to continue to cover their needs, so fewer people would be able to find out </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">about the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consultation from these sources.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We therefore need an effective consultation so that people have had a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">proper</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> chance to find out about it and respond.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li st